===Etymology===
From {{der|en|de|Antisemitismus}}, which was coined in 1879 by German political agitator [[w:Wilhelm Marr|Wilhelm Marr]] to replace {{m|de|Judenhaß|lit=Jew-hatred}} to make hatred of the Jews seem rational and sanctioned by scientific knowledge. The similar term {{m|de|antisemitisch|t=anti-semitic}} was first used in 1860, by Jewish scholar [[w:Moritz Steinschneider|Moritz Steinschneider]]. See [[w: Antisemitism#Origin and usage|Wikipedia's article on the etymology and usage of the term]].

The term is superficially/synchronically equivalent to {{af|en|anti-|Semitism}} (see {{m|en|Semite}}), for which reason it is rarely extended to cover prejudice against ''any'' Semitic people, or against adherents of any of the religions that originated among the Semitic peoples (the Abrahamic religions). See [[#Usage_notes|the usage notes]].

