====Usage notes====
* Though {{m|en|Semitic}} refers in a broader sense to all those who speak Semitic languages (including e.g. [[w:Arab|Arabs]] and [[w:Assyrian people|Assyrians]]), the term ''anti-Semitism'' has historically referred to prejudice against Jews alone. To avoid the confusion of the [[misnomer]], many scholars of the subject (such as [[w:Emil Fackenheim|Emil Fackenheim]]) now favor the unhyphenated ''antisemitism'' in order to emphasize that the word should be read as a single unified term, not as a meaningful root word-prefix combination.<ref>{{cite-web |title=Antisemitism. The Power of Myth (Facing History), ''Defining Antisemitism'' page 2 (PDF page 5) |url=http://www.facinghistory.org/campus/reslib.nsf/99ca830bb4f483948525717f005abfc7/2820f36c177cc758852571860065e8c2/$FILE/complete_antisemitism.pdf |accessdate=2 August 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807224502/http://www.facinghistory.org/campus/reslib.nsf/99ca830bb4f483948525717f005abfc7/2820f36c177cc758852571860065e8c2/$FILE/complete_antisemitism.pdf |archivedate=7 August 2007 }}</ref><ref>“…the spelling ought to be antisemitism without the hyphen, dispelling the notion that there is an entity 'Semitism' which 'anti-Semitism' opposes.” -- Emil Fackenheim, ''Post-Holocaust Anti-Jewishness, Jewish Identity and the Centrality of Israel'', in '''World Jewry and the State of Israel'''. ed. Moshe David, p11, n2.</ref><ref>“Antisemitism is not a scientific word, and it is entitled to neither a hyphen nor a capital.” Dr. James Parkes, 1953, quoted in [https://web.archive.org/web/20070610081851/http://www.nizkor.org/ftp.cgi/people/i/irving.david/jackel/postscript-kirk-6 Holocaust Almanac: David Irving's Hitler: Postscript]</ref> (See Wikipedia's article on [[w: Antisemitism#Etymology and usage|the etymology and usage]] of the term.) Use of the term to refer to prejudice against any Semitic people is rare and nonstandard.
* Some use the term to hatred/prejudice against speakers of Hebrew, Arabic, Syriac, or any other [[Semitic]] language, as well as ethnic and religious groups associated with these languages.
* A very small number of writers use the term to refer to prejudice against Muslims, apparently considering them to constitute a [[Semitic]] [[race]] (citation needed, and contradiction-inline, see talk) as opposed to only a [[religion]]. See [[Citations:anti-Semitism|citations]].

